  array('id' => '2378','book_id' => 'B03819','title' => 'Trout Flies; Naturals and Imitations','author' => 'Wetzel,Charles','publication_year' => '1955','publisher' => 'The Stackpole Company','edition' => '1st','pages' => '152','size' => '8','book_condition' => 'VF','jacket_condition' => 'NDJ','cost_price' => '50','valuation' => '200','add_date' => '09/2018','sold_date' => NULL,'sold_price' => NULL,'buyer_name' => NULL,'buyer_email' => NULL,'comment' => 'Stackpole Company, Harrisburg, 1955, first printing. Illustrated with b&w drawings. 8" x 10.75". Tan paper covered boards, sporting bookplate of Wm. Naden on the front endpaper. 152 pp. "All important hatches are catalogued according to scientific and angling nomenclature, and the emergence dates are listed. Time tested imitations are suggested along with tying specifications and instructions". Chapters on fishing the wet and dry fly, and the nymph, excerpts from Wetzel\'s fishing diary, etc. "A valuable and important work. Chapter 10 adds material to the Quill Gordon story. Scarce." (Bruns','status' => NULL),
  array('id' => '2379','book_id' => 'B03820','title' => 'Tips','author' => 'Kelson,Geo.M','publication_year' => '1901','publisher' => 'author','edition' => '1st','pages' => '171','size' => '7','book_condition' => 'Spine sl faded butt gilt is bright and clear - overall VG+','jacket_condition' => 'NDJAP','cost_price' => '100','valuation' => '500','add_date' => '09/2018','sold_date' => NULL,'sold_price' => NULL,'buyer_name' => NULL,'buyer_email' => NULL,'comment' => 'Published by the author. London. 1901 1st edition. 8 (190 x 250mm). Ppxiv,168 + 11pp ads. B/w illustrations. Burgundy pictorial cloth gilt with bevelled edges. Pages are quite browned but a very good clean copy. This copy has advertisements for Kelson\'s \'The Salmon Fly\' tipped in at pages 14 and 158. "George Kelson\'s Tips was published in 1901 by the author and includes pages of the marvellous contemporary advertisements by which Kelson financed his printing. Anyone interested in the great era of the late 19th century salmon fishing will find this book a must. His comments on the latest tackle and flies are fascinating, all couched in characteristic High Victorian prose. The book gives hints on the rod to select, the fly to use, methods of casting, wading and knots, and general riverside tips. He finishes the book with a few pages of reviews of his book The Salmon Fly.','status' => NULL),
