  array('id' => '3499','book_id' => 'B03761','title' => 'Salmon of the World','author' => 'Schwiebert,Ernest','publication_year' => '1970','publisher' => 'Winchester Press','edition' => '1st Limited (171/750)','pages' => '63','size' => '10','book_condition' => 'VF and plates also in mint condition','jacket_condition' => 'NDJAP. Slipocase in F condition except for a few white spots on rear','cost_price' => '75','valuation' => '400','add_date' => '02/2018','sold_date' => NULL,'sold_price' => NULL,'buyer_name' => NULL,'buyer_email' => NULL,'comment' => 'Winchester Press, 1970. Hardcover. Condition: Near Fine. Dust Jacket Condition: Near Fine. 1st Edition. 12 in. by 16 in. Illus. Unnumbered copy of 750 Copies. Foreword by Arnold Gingrich. Illustrated with 30 looseleaf plates of salmon, this includes the Pacific salmon, Atlantic salmon and all landlocked forms, plus the many Asian/European species including Huchen and Brachymystax. There is included a very complete review of salmon literature from Pliny to Haig-Brown. This copy is unmarked internally. The book and looseleaf Salmon illustrations are as-new. The slipcase shows just a minimum of shelf wear.Schwiebert was a skilled illustrator and water-colourist. This latter talent is placed on display in Salmon of the World , an opulent port9 of portraits of all the species of the King of Gamefish. While still an undergraduate, Schwiebert wrote his first book, Matching the Hatch (1955), which astonished the American angling community by realizing American anglingâ€™s most avidly desired, yet most unattainable, theoretical goal: reconciling traditional artificial fly patterns and their use in actual practice with Science. The bookâ€™s title became a by-word for the preferred methodology of serious dry fly fishermen everywhere. In a single step, the youthful Schwiebert vaulted to the supreme heights of angling authority; and, over the years, other publications appropriate to his sporting stature followed. Architectural training had taught him draftsmanship, and he subsequently became a skilled illustrator and water-colorist. This latter talent was placed on display in Salmon of the World (1970), an opulent port9 of portraits of all the species of the King of Gamefish, produced in a small edition, and much coveted by collectors. With Nymphs (1973), Schwiebert proceeded so far into entomology that he passed beyond nearly all of his readersâ€™ ability to follow. The boxed two-volume Trout (1978) at some 1800 pages length was intentionally monumental, and simply overwhelming, covering angling history, species biology, techniques, and featuring a rhapsodic and passionately detailed survey of high end tackle. Schwiebert wrote regularly for angling, and other sporting, serials, and published three collections of stories and memoirs: Remembrances of Rivers Past (1973), Death of a Riverkeeper (1980), and A River for Christmas (1988).','status' => NULL),
  array('id' => '3500','book_id' => 'B03755','title' => 'The Making of a Trout Stream','author' => 'Taverner,Eric','publication_year' => '1953','publisher' => 'Seeley','edition' => '1st Ltd (1/250)','pages' => '140','size' => '7','book_condition' => 'Mint - signed by author','jacket_condition' => 'Slipcase - mint','cost_price' => '20','valuation' => '40','add_date' => '02/2018','sold_date' => NULL,'sold_price' => NULL,'buyer_name' => NULL,'buyer_email' => NULL,'comment' => 'Seeley, Service & Co., London, (1953), one of 250 copies. Illustrated with fine woodcuts. 6" x 8.25". 140 pp. White cloth, map endpapers. ".the story.of a rather ordinary trout stream.a tranquil account of problems slowly solved.problems of water weed, fishes and their food.". Improving a trout fishery. Fine in very good slipcase and signed by author.','status' => NULL),
